        <div class="section">
            <div class="section-intro">
                <h2>Reading bitcoin through the Power Law</h2>
                <p><em>Why this isn&rsquo;t 2013 bitcoin &mdash; and why today&rsquo;s price may be the most useful signal on the chart.</em></p>
            </div>

            <p class="prose">Every cyclical top in bitcoin&rsquo;s history was visible as a top in real time. Every cycle floor was visible as a floor. The pattern isn&rsquo;t subtle when you plot bitcoin&rsquo;s price against its long-run <a href="/the-power-law.html">Power Law trend</a> &mdash; tops register as measurable deviations above trend; floors register as measurable deviations below it. The chart below plots both across 16 years of price history, plus today&rsquo;s position.</p>

            <div class="bvsm-chart-wrap">
                <div class="bvsm-chart-label">Bitcoin price vs. Power Law trend, with cyclical-top and floor markers</div>
                <div class="bvsm-chart-canvas-tall">
                    <canvas id="bvsmPowerLawChart" role="img" aria-label="Bitcoin price plotted against the Power Law trend across 16 years, with annotated markers at each cyclical top showing the trend-deviation multiple, each cycle floor showing its trend-deviation multiple, and the current position at 0.59× trend."></canvas>
                </div>
                <p class="bvsm-chart-caption">Historical BTC price (white) vs. Power Law trend (dashed amber), log-scale Y axis. Numbers next to each marker are the cycle&rsquo;s trend-deviation multiple. Top markers (rust) register at &ge;1.0&times; trend; floor markers (sage) at &le;1.0&times; trend. Today&rsquo;s position is highlighted at 0.59&times; &mdash; well below trend, inside the historical floor band.</p>
            </div>

            <p class="prose">Two things are immediately visible in the chart that qualitative narratives about bitcoin tend to miss.</p>

            <p class="prose"><strong>First, tops are getting smaller.</strong> Bitcoin&rsquo;s cyclical peaks have compressed dramatically: 12.1&times; over trend in 2013, 6.4&times; in 2017, 2.8&times; in 2021, and just 1.1&times; in both the March 2024 top and the October 2025 all-time high. (The 12.1&times; in 2013 reflects early bitcoin&rsquo;s pre-institutional regime, when retail-driven overshoots were far more violent than anything since &mdash; and the compression from 12&times; to 1.1&times; <em>is</em> the maturation evidence.) The euphoric overshoots that defined the early asset have faded every cycle. This is the maturation thesis &mdash; institutional capital, regulated ETF flows, roughly 6.4% of supply held in ETPs, treasury allocations at 49+ public companies, 23 nation-state holders &mdash; rendered as a single visual fact: tops aren&rsquo;t what they used to be.</p>

            <p class="prose"><strong>Second, floors have stayed structurally stable.</strong> Across four different cycles spanning a 90&times; range of absolute prices, the cycle bottoms have all registered between 0.41&times; and 0.66&times; trend &mdash; a tight band. The downside reference hasn&rsquo;t moved while the upside has compressed toward it. The within-cycle entry-price spread has gone from 22&times; (2013 top vs. 2015 floor) to 1.7&times; (2024 March top vs. 2024 August dip). Timing matters less now than it used to; the boundaries are tighter on both sides.</p>

            <p class="prose"><strong>And today sits at 0.59&times; trend</strong> &mdash; squarely inside the historical floor range, between the 2022 post-FTX low (0.41&times;) and the 2024 mid-cycle dip (0.66&times;). By the framework&rsquo;s own logic, this is structurally favorable entry territory: bitcoin is roughly 41% below where its long-run trend says it should be, while the October 2025 all-time high only managed 12% above trend. Bitcoin has spent more &ldquo;distance&rdquo; below trend than above it in this cycle.</p>

            <p class="prose">The chart isn&rsquo;t a forecast &mdash; the Power Law is a central-tendency expectation, not a prediction, and the asset can stay below or above trend for extended periods. The point is that you have a structural reference for reading entry quality in real time. The scenarios below stress-test that reference against the worst-case version of itself: what would have happened if you&rsquo;d actually bought at each of the five cyclical tops marked above? The answer rhymes across every cycle &mdash; and it isn&rsquo;t what the &ldquo;what if I&rsquo;d bought the top&rdquo; objection assumes.</p>
        </div>


