            <p class="prose">Each of the five top markers on the chart above represents a moment a buyer might (reasonably) call the worst possible entry. The calculator below stress-tests that scenario three ways: as a single <strong>lump sum</strong> invested on that day and held to today, as <strong>weekly DCA</strong> starting that day and continuing through today, or as a lump sum <strong>held N years</strong> from the start date (the horizon-locked view, which gives all five presets the same elapsed time to compound). Compare against the same dollar amount or weekly cadence in the S&amp;P 500 (total return, with dividends reinvested) and the NASDAQ-100 (total return). The five presets match the top markers on the chart one-for-one; the worst-case lens deliberately stays anchored on entries the framework calls structurally bad.</p>

            <p class="prose">DCA mode smooths the worst-timing risk because most of the dollars get deployed at prices other than the peak. Horizon mode handles the older-vs-recent-top problem the lump-sum-to-today mode runs into &mdash; the 2024 and 2025 tops have had less time to compound than the 2013 and 2017 tops, which makes a held-to-today comparison apples-to-oranges. <strong>Horizon mode locks the elapsed time across presets:</strong> at a 10-year horizon, the 2013 and 2017 results are historical fact, while the 2021/2024/2025 results combine historical data through today plus a forward projection from today using the Power Law trend (for bitcoin) and the long-run historical CAGRs (for the equity comparators). Whether the resulting positions favor bitcoin or the equity comparators is the question the calculator answers &mdash; and the answer, for every anchor date the page tests at a horizon longer than ~3 years, is bitcoin.</p>

