            <p class="prose"><em>The 2025-top preset deserves a specific caveat in either mode.</em> It&rsquo;s the most recent cyclical top covered here and has had the least time to play out &mdash; bitcoin reached its all-time high of approximately $126K on October 6, 2025, and as of this writing in mid-2026 the price sits roughly 35% below that level. If you started from that scenario in lump-sum mode, your hold has been less than a year and you may currently be underwater on the comparison against the S&amp;P 500. The page&rsquo;s argument depends on long-enough holding periods. The 2017-top and 2021-top presets show what the same scenario tends to look like after five-plus years of patience.</p>

            <p class="prose"><strong>A note on DCA versus lump-sum, since the page is being fair to the reader who&rsquo;d ease in:</strong> <a href="https://investor.vanguard.com/investor-resources-education/online-trading/dollar-cost-averaging-vs-lump-sum" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Vanguard&rsquo;s research</a> on this question &mdash; across decades of equity-market history &mdash; finds that <strong>lump-sum investing beats dollar-cost averaging in roughly two-thirds of historical 12-month windows</strong>. The mechanism is simple: markets spend more time going up than down, so deploying capital later (on average) means buying at higher prices. DCA&rsquo;s value is real, but it&rsquo;s primarily a <em>regret-minimization</em> tool that prevents the worst single-day-entry outcome, not a return-maximization strategy. The page leads with the lump-sum-at-the-top scenarios precisely because they&rsquo;re the most-feared outcome &mdash; if the historical record handles even those cases at the horizons that matter, the case for DCA-as-a-better-alternative gets weaker, not stronger.</p>
